Author: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>
Commit: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>

    K2.A.1 dtype hotfix: cast round-tripped K/V to working dtype before index_copy_
    
    Surfaces the bug the user hit on Mac mini 2026-06-09:
    
        RuntimeError: index_copy_(): self and source expected to have
        the same dtype, but got (self) BFloat16 and (source) Float
    
    at inference_engine/v04/dlm_restored_verifier.py:476 in
    _round_trip_resident_through_compressor.
    
    Root cause:
    
      KakeyaLattice's decompress returns fp32 tensors on the codec's
      compute device (typically CPU), but the verifier's working K/V
      tensors are bf16/fp16 on MPS/CUDA. index_copy_ is dtype-strict
      AND device-strict, so the assignment crashes without an explicit
      cast.
    
      The K2.A.2 stateful path (_V04SessionCache.update, lines 376-381
      + 402-413) already handles this: it casts the decompressed K/V to
      the working dtype/device before scattering. The comment at line 379
      even acknowledges 'per K2.A.1 fix for bf16 mismatch' — but the K2.A.1
      stateless path at _round_trip_resident_through_compressor was
      never patched. PR #87 (the historical 'bf16 hotfix') landed the cast
      at the K2.A.2 site only, not retroactively at the K2.A.1 site.
    
      Result: K2.A.1 stateless mode worked on CUDA bf16 by accident
      (MPS-only failure mode? — TBD; we didn't catch it because the
      K2.A.1 vast evidence may have run on a path that bypassed the
      resident round-trip when KL OFF, and KL ON CUDA bf16 happened to
      cast somewhere upstream). The K2.A.2 stateful production smoke
      on Mac M4 MPS bf16 is the first path to hit this site without an
      upstream cast, and crashes immediately.
    
    Fix:
    
      Cast K_round_tripped / V_round_tripped to (device, dtype) of K_out /
      V_out before index_copy_. Mirrors the cast at line 380 and 408
      in the stateful path.
    
    Regression test:
    
      tests/inference_engine/v04/test_dlm_restored_verifier.py adds
      TestRoundTripResidentHelper.test_bf16_inputs_accept_fp32_round_tripped_decompress
      which simulates the exact crash signature: bf16 K/V inputs + a
      compressor whose decompress returns fp32 (emulating KakeyaLattice's
      actual behaviour on Mac MPS / CUDA bf16 paths). Pre-fix the test
      raises RuntimeError with the exact message the user reported;
      post-fix the helper returns a bf16 tensor with values approximately
      equal to the input.
    
      Verified: stashing the fix and re-running the test reproduces the
      user's exact RuntimeError; un-stashing and re-running passes 281/281.
    
    Scope concern:
    
      This fix is in v0.4 K2.A.1 code (PR #84 / merged), not in this PR's
      natural surface area (the Mac reviewer scripts). It belongs in a
      proper hotfix PR off the K2.A.1 codebase that backports cleanly
      to PR #84's lineage. But:
    
        1. The user is actively waiting to run the production smoke and
           re-establish the K2.A.2 acceptance evidence,
        2. The bug literally blocks any KL ON path from running on any
           bf16 Mac M4 / non-CUDA device,
        3. The fix is 6 lines of code with a regression test that proves
           both the bug and the fix.
    
      Carrying the fix on the Mac reviewer branch is the unblock path;
      a clean backport PR off the K2.A.1 codebase will follow once the
      v04 stack settles, so the fix lands properly in the K2.A.1 code
      history and not as a Mac-reviewer side effect.
    
    Lessons codified for the K2.A.1 codebase:
    
      * Any K/V tensor manipulation involving an external codec MUST
        bracket the codec's input + output with explicit
        .to(device=..., dtype=...) calls. index_copy_ is one
        of several APIs that crash on dtype mismatch (vs silently
        upcasting). Other risky APIs in this codebase: index_add_,
        masked_scatter_, index_put_.
      * The K2.A.2 site at line 379-381 has a comment 'per K2.A.1 fix
        for bf16 mismatch' — that comment was misleading because the
        'fix' it references was incomplete. After this PR, both K2.A.1
        and K2.A.2 sites are consistent. Future contributors editing
        either site should leave a cross-reference.
    
    Tests:
      tests/inference_engine/v04/: 281 passed (280 existing + 1 new
                                  regression test)
    
    Stack:
      This commit is on the Mac reviewer branch (#94) on top of the
      cherry-picked Mac reviewer commit. PR #94 base is
      AgentMemory/v04-pr-adr-k3-gemma4-model-identity-lock-8e7f (#92).
    
    Co-authored-by: FluffyAIcode <FluffyAIcode@users.noreply.github.com>

