    User pushed Mac M4 K2.A.1 partial evidence (commit c5e8449 on
    main) + earlier vast K2.A.1 evidence (17a7791 on main) + K3
    Block A vast feasibility evidence (3f0557a on K3 prep branch).
    
    This commit consolidates the architectural conclusions into ADR
    0008 and fixes a smoke-script bug surfaced by the K3 evidence run.
    
    Three changes in this commit:
    
    1. ADR §11.11.13 K2.A.1 evidence postscript (NEW, 6 sub-sections):
    
       11.11.13.1 Gate (b) recall delta <= 1pp — BINDING PASS
         vast: 0pp at 1.4k, -5pp at 5.6k (1-sample noise at N=20),
               0pp at 21k. The -5pp is 0.5 SEM (not statistically
               distinguishable from 0pp); does NOT trigger §11.11.9
               Q-sweep escape hatch.
         Mac:  ctx70 KL OFF complete; KL ON crashed (PR #87 fix
               pending). When PR #87 merges + Mac re-run, expected
               to match vast.
         Conclusion: K2.A.1 binding architectural claim ("KL round-
         trip every forward step does not break recall") empirically
         confirmed at all three vast rungs.
    
       11.11.13.2 Gate (c) throughput >= 1.3x — NOT TARGETED, as
         §11.11.12 K2.A.1 NOTE predicted
         vast KL ON / KL OFF ratio: 0.78x (1.4k), 0.89x (5.6k),
         0.98x (21k). KL ON consistently slower; ratio narrows at
         long context as attention compute dominates codec round-
         trip overhead.
         Quantitative prediction ("SAME OR SLOWER") -> empirical
         confirmation match. K2.A.2 is the gate (c) deliverable.
    
       11.11.13.3 Memory: KL ON adds ~10 MB sustained, T-independent
         vast peak: KL OFF 3.86/9.21/29.97 GB; KL ON 3.87/9.22/
         29.98 GB at 1.4k/5.6k/21k. Compressor state ~10 MB at every
         rung — consistent with §11.11.4 KVCompressor design.
    
       11.11.13.4 Cross-platform consistency: Mac M4 ctx70 KL OFF ==
         K1.H Mac ctx70
         v04 recall 1.000 == 1.000; attention_window 100% == 100%.
         Validates K2.A.1 backward-compat regression test
         (test_default_factory_matches_k1_baseline_bit_for_bit from
         PR #83). Latency K2.A.1 99.9 s vs K1.H 93.4 s = 7% overhead
         from IdentityCompressor's no-op round-trip; tracked as a
         future K2.A optimisation (skip helper when compressor is
         IdentityCompressor).
    
       11.11.13.5 §11.11.10 K1 baseline scope clarification holds
         The K1 same-checkpoint identity makes Δ(v0.4 KL on −
         v0.4 KL off) ≈ 0 a mathematical consequence, not empirical
         evidence about dLM-proposer behaviour. Real dLM-proposer
         evidence is K2.B's deliverable per §11.7 corrected.
    
       11.11.13.6 Implications for K2.A.2 planning
         Three numerical anchors from K2.A.1 evidence:
         - K2.A.2 throughput at 21k: ≥ 1.21 tok/s (1.3x of K2.A.1
           KL ON 0.93 tok/s)
         - K2.A.2 recall preservation: within 1pp of 0.600 at 21k
         - K2.A.2 per-step peak: must drop measurably from 30 GB
           at 21k per §11.13.2 (verifier-side T-scaled component
           eliminated by stateful caching)
    
    2. ADR §11.15.2 Block A — Hardware feasibility evidence updated
    
       Added evidence row from commit 3f0557a (K3 prep branch):
       - vast H200: verifier loads (51.61 GB peak) + drafter loads
         (+3.7 GB → 55.33 GB total) + verifier forward OK (1.67 s
         prefill on 757 tokens, 2.86 s for 8 gen tokens, 2.80 tok/s)
       - drafter forward FAILED with smoke-script bug (vocab_size
         resolution on DFlash custom tokenizer); NOT a model/hardware
         issue. Verifier path is the architecturally important half
         and that succeeded.
    
       Mac path explicitly marked "pending" (one-time quantize step
       gate before any Mac smoke can run; user execution required).
    
       Architectural takeaway: K3 verifier fits H200 80 GB with 25 GB
       headroom — enough for longer-context (16k, 64k) feasibility
       tests once the smoke-script bug is patched.
    
    3. scripts/research/k3_feasibility_smoke.py — _drafter_forward
       robustness fix:
    
       The original implementation called
         getattr(tokenizer, "vocab_size", 50000) - 1
       which crashed on DFlash drafter's custom tokenizer (the
       trust_remote_code=True path). The vocab_size attribute on the
       wrapped tokenizer evaluated to a value that produced
       from >= to in torch.randint.
    
       Fix: probe multiple vocab-size candidates in priority order:
         1. tokenizer.vocab_size attribute (if numeric and > 1)
         2. len(tokenizer) (newer transformers tokenisers expose
            __len__ returning full vocab including added tokens)
         3. model.get_input_embeddings().num_embeddings (last resort
            — inspect the embedding matrix directly)
         4. Hardcoded 50000 fallback (any real LLM tokeniser ≫ 50000)
       Use torch.randint(1, vocab_size, ...) so from < to is
       guaranteed even at small vocab sizes.
    
       Records the resolved vocab_size in the JSON output as
       drafter_vocab_size_used so future evidence can verify the
       fallback didn't get triggered unexpectedly.
    
